a9b326df4e6da61c5b6f5e1058be83a2 (00:45): b25b6b77a0087ff8385941e5545d32ea: I was reading a text that describes V-V compounds
a9b326df4e6da61c5b6f5e1058be83a2 (00:45): compound verbs
a9b326df4e6da61c5b6f5e1058be83a2 (00:45): Japanese compound verbs
a9b326df4e6da61c5b6f5e1058be83a2 (00:46): and it says there are two types of Japanese V-V compounds
a9b326df4e6da61c5b6f5e1058be83a2 (00:46): one is lexical V-V compounds
a9b326df4e6da61c5b6f5e1058be83a2 (00:46): which is the normal kind that most such verbs fall into
a9b326df4e6da61c5b6f5e1058be83a2 (00:46): the second time is syntactic V-V compounds
a9b326df4e6da61c5b6f5e1058be83a2 (00:47): in which the second verb in the pair is a verb that relates to beginning, ending, or continuing something
a9b326df4e6da61c5b6f5e1058be83a2 (00:47): which verbs are apparently called "aspectual" verbs
b25b6b77a0087ff8385941e5545d32ea (00:50): As in http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Grammatical_aspect I assume
